<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-09-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-09-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="1466" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1466">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.41/30.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">British
                                        Ambassador</gloss>.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-09-29">
                                        <hi rend="italic">September 29, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: I beg to
                                acknowledge the receipt of your note of August 31, wherein you
                                suggest that, when American Consular officers or other officials in
                                Mexico receive intimation of any steps or events likely to affect
                                the safety of foreigners, they may at once impart their knowledge to
                                all foreigners alike.</p>
                            <p>In reply I beg to advise you that instructions in the sense indicated
                                had already been given to all American Consuls in Mexico.</p>
                            <p>In this relation I beg also to advise you that the United States
                                Transport <hi rend="italic">Buford</hi>, now on the west coast of
                                Mexico for the purpose of bringing out refugees, has been instructed
                                to furnish transportation to any foreigners who desire to leave
                                Mexico, in so far as the capacity of the vessel will permit.</p>
                            <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">John E. Osborne</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>